Horace and Virgil were closely united by the bonds of affection and friendship, as well as by similarity of taste and kinds-ed pur- suits.

This ode was written on the embarkation of Virgil for Athens, where he expected to meet the emperor, on his return from Asia. Virgil had intended to accompany Augustus in 1115 eastern expe- dition, but was prevented by ill health. He, however, met him at Athens, but he was soon aster taken ill at Megara, and brought back to Italy at his own request, and lauded at Brundusium3 where he died a few days after.
